-- Stocks in South Africa Gain, Led By Anglo Platinum, BHP Billiton and Sasol
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-07-13T12:42:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-13/south-african-stocks-fall-for-second-day-led-lower-by-anglo-bhp-sasol.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose 231.02, or 0.9 percent, to 27,423.33 at 2:34
p.m. in Johannesburg, heading for its highest close since June
23.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ) climbed 4.27 rand, or 1.4
percent, to 317.60 rand. Africa’s largest gold producer said a
government suspension of operations at most of its Tau Lekoa
mine in South Africa has been lifted.  
 Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ) rose 13.40 rand, or 1.9
percent, to 733.91 rand, heading for its biggest gain in a week.
The world’s biggest platinum producer said first-half profit
rose as much as 15 percent from a year earlier as metal prices
climbed.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, rallied 2.06 rand, or 1 percent, to 212.51 rand, paring
yesterday’s 1.3 percent drop.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ)
increased 2.69 rand, or 1 percent, to 278.07 rand. Copper for
three-month delivery erased a drop of as much as 1.1 percent on
the London Metal Exchange and traded 0.2 percent stronger at
$6,640 a metric ton.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose 5.20 rand, or 1.9 percent, to 285.20 rand,
erasing an earlier 1.1 percent slide. Crude oil advanced in New
York as rising equity markets and forecasts of declining U.S.
inventories signaled growing demand for fuel.  
